# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: subdivision-surfaces
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] The **Catmull–Clark** algorithm is a technique used in 3D computer graphics to create curved surfaces by using subdivision surface modeling.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] It was devised by Edwin Catmull and Jim Clark in 1978 as a generalization of bi-cubic *uniform* B-spline surfaces to arbitrary topology.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] In 2005/06, Edwin Catmull, together with Tony DeRose and Jos Stam, received an Academy Award for Technical Achievement for their invention and application of subdivision surfaces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] DeRose wrote about "efficient, fair interpolation" and character animation.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] Stam described a technique for a direct evaluation of the limit surface without recursion.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] Start with a mesh of an arbitrary polyhedron.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] All the vertices in this mesh shall be called *original points*.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] The new mesh will consist only of quadrilaterals, which in general will *not* be planar.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] The new mesh will generally look "smoother" (i.e. less "jagged" or "pointy") than the old mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] Repeated subdivision results in meshes that are more and more rounded.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] The arbitrary-looking barycenter formula was chosen by Catmull and Clark based on the aesthetic appearance of the resulting surfaces rather than on a mathematical derivation, although they do go to great lengths to rigorously show that the method converges to bicubic B-spline surfaces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] It can be shown that the limit surface obtained by this refinement process is $G^{1}$ (tangent plane) continuous at extraordinary vertices (valence not equal to 4) and ${\mathcal {C}}^{2}$ continuous at regular points (valence equal to 4).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] (when *n* indicates how many derivatives are continuous, we speak of ${\mathcal {C}}^{n}$ continuity).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] After one iteration, the number of extraordinary points on the surface remains constant.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] The limit surface of Catmull–Clark subdivision surfaces can also be evaluated directly, without any recursive refinement.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] This can be accomplished by means of the technique of Jos Stam (1998).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] This method reformulates the recursive refinement process into a matrix exponential problem, which can be solved directly by means of matrix diagonalization.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] Catmull–Clark surfaces were extended to support semi-sharp creases by using different subdivision rules for a fixed number of iterations determined by a sharpness value.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/catmull-clark-subdivision-surface] This approach, introduced by Tony DeRose et al. in 1998, allows for a controllable transition from sharp to smooth subdivision rules.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] In 3D computer graphics, a **Doo–Sabin subdivision surface** is a type of subdivision surface based on a generalization of *bi-quadratic* uniform B-splines, whereas Catmull-Clark was based on generalized *bi-cubic* uniform B-splines.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] The subdivision refinement algorithm was developed in 1978 by Daniel Doo and Malcolm Sabin.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] The Doo-Sabin process generates one new face at each original vertex, ⁠ n ⁠ new faces along each original edge, and ⁠ $n^{2}$ ⁠ new faces at each original face.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] A primary characteristic of the Doo–Sabin subdivision method is the creation of four faces and four edges (*valence* 4) around every new vertex in the refined mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] A drawback is that the faces created at the original vertices may be triangles or n-gons that are not necessarily coplanar.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] Doo–Sabin surfaces are defined recursively.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] Like all subdivision procedures, each refinement iteration, following the procedure given, replaces the current mesh with a "smoother", more refined mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] In subdivision terminology, Doo-Sabin is a dual quadrilateral scheme: unlike Catmull-Clark, its topological refinement step splits vertices rather than faces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] After many iterations, the surface will gradually converge onto a smooth limit surface.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] Later work has noted that classical Doo-Sabin subdivision can exhibit shape defects near extraordinary points; for convex input meshes these include flatness at the extraordinary point and nearby oscillation.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] Just as for Catmull–Clark surfaces, Doo–Sabin limit surfaces can also be *evaluated directly* without any recursive refinement, by means of the technique of Jos Stam.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/doo-sabin-subdivision-surface] The solution is, however, not as computationally efficient as for Catmull–Clark surfaces because the Doo–Sabin subdivision matrices are not (in general) diagonalizable.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/loop-subdivision-surface] In computer graphics, the **Loop method** for subdivision surfaces is an approximating subdivision scheme developed by Charles Loop in 1987 for triangular meshes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/loop-subdivision-surface] Prior methods, namely Catmull-Clark and Doo-Sabin, focused on quad meshes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/loop-subdivision-surface] Loop subdivision surfaces are defined recursively, dividing each triangle into four smaller ones.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/loop-subdivision-surface] The method is based on a quartic box spline.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/loop-subdivision-surface] It generates C2 continuous limit surfaces everywhere except at extraordinary vertices, where they are C1 continuous.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In mathematics, a **spline** is a function defined piecewise by polynomials.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In interpolating problems, spline interpolation is often preferred to polynomial interpolation because it yields similar results, even when using low degree polynomials, while avoiding Runge's phenomenon for higher degrees.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In the computer science subfields of computer-aided design and computer graphics, the term *spline* more frequently refers to a piecewise polynomial (parametric) curve.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Splines are popular curves in these subfields because of the simplicity of their construction, their ease and accuracy of evaluation, and their capacity to approximate complex shapes through curve fitting and interactive curve design.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The term spline comes from the flexible spline devices used by shipbuilders and draftsmen to draw smooth shapes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The term "spline" is used to refer to a wide class of functions that are used in applications requiring data interpolation and/or smoothing.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The data may be either one-dimensional or multi-dimensional.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Spline functions for interpolation are normally determined as the minimizers of suitable measures of roughness (for example integral squared curvature) subject to the interpolation constraints.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Smoothing splines may be viewed as generalizations of interpolation splines where the functions are determined to minimize a weighted combination of the average squared approximation error over observed data and the roughness measure.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] For a number of meaningful definitions of the roughness measure, the spline functions are found to be finite dimensional in nature, which is the primary reason for their utility in computations and representation.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] For the rest of this section, we focus entirely on one-dimensional, polynomial splines and use the term "spline" in this restricted sense.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] According to Gerald Farin, B-splines were explored as early as the nineteenth century by Nikolai Lobachevsky at Kazan University in Russia.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Before computers were used, numerical calculations were done by hand.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Although piecewise-defined functions like the sign function or step function were used, polynomials were generally preferred because they were easier to work with.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Through the advent of computers, splines have gained importance.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] They were first used as a replacement for polynomials in interpolation, then as a tool to construct smooth and flexible shapes in computer graphics.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] It is commonly accepted that the first mathematical reference to splines is the 1946 paper by Schoenberg, which is probably the first place that the word "spline" is used in connection with smooth, piecewise polynomial approximation.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] However, the ideas have their roots in the aircraft and shipbuilding industries.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] For years the practice of ship design had employed models to design in the small.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The successful design was then plotted on graph paper and the key points of the plot were re-plotted on larger graph paper to full size.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The thin wooden strips provided an interpolation of the key points into smooth curves.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The strips would be held in place at discrete points (called "ducks" by Forrest; Schoenberg used "dogs" or "rats") and between these points would assume shapes of minimum strain energy.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] According to Forrest, one possible impetus for a mathematical model for this process was the potential loss of the critical design components for an entire aircraft should the loft be hit by an enemy bomb.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] This gave rise to "conic lofting", which used conic sections to model the position of the curve between the ducks.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Conic lofting was replaced by what we would call splines in the early 1960s based on work by J.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Ferguson at Boeing and (somewhat later) by Malcolm A.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The word "spline" was originally an East Anglian dialect word.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The use of splines for modeling automobile bodies seems to have several independent beginnings.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Credit is claimed on behalf of de Casteljau at Citroën, Pierre Bézier at Renault, and Birkhoff, Garabedian, and de Boor at General Motors (see Birkhoff and de Boor, 1965), all for work occurring in the very early 1960s or late 1950s.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] At least one of de Casteljau's papers was published, but not widely, in 1959.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] De Boor's work at General Motors resulted in a number of papers being published in the early 1960s, including some of the fundamental work on B-splines.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Work was also being done at Pratt & Whitney Aircraft, where two of the authors of (Ahlberg et al., 1967) — the first book-length treatment of splines — were employed, and the David Taylor Model Basin, by Feodor Theilheimer.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The work at General Motors is detailed nicely in (Birkhoff, 1990) and (Young, 1997).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Davis (1997) summarizes some of this material.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] We begin by limiting our discussion to polynomials in one variable.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In this case, a spline is a piecewise polynomial function.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] This function, call it S, takes values from an interval [*a*,*b*] and maps them to $\mathbb {R} ,$ the set of real numbers, $S:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R} .$ We want S to be piecewise defined.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The given *k* + 1 points ti are called **knots**.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The vector **t** = (*t*0, …, *tk*) is called a **knot vector** for the spline.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] If the knots are equidistantly distributed in the interval [*a*,*b*] we say the spline is **uniform**, otherwise we say it is **non-uniform**.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] If the polynomial pieces Pi each have degree at most n, then the spline is said to be of **degree** ≤ *n* (or of **order** *n* + 1).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] If $S\in C^{r_{i}}$ in a neighborhood of ti, then the spline is said to be of smoothness (at least) $C^{r_{i}}$ at ti.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A vector **r** = (*r*1, …, *r**k*–1) such that the spline has smoothness $C^{r_{i}}$ at ti for *i* = 1, …, *k* – 1 is called a **smoothness vector** for the spline.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Given a knot vector **t**, a degree n, and a smoothness vector **r** for **t**, one can consider the set of all splines of degree ≤ *n* having knot vector **t** and smoothness vector **r**.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Equipped with the operation of adding two functions (pointwise addition) and taking real multiples of functions, this set becomes a real vector space.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In the mathematical study of polynomial splines the question of what happens when two knots, say ti and *t**i*+1, are taken to approach one another and become coincident has an easy answer.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The polynomial piece *Pi*(*t*) disappears, and the pieces *P**i*−1(*t*) and *P**i*+1(*t*) join with the sum of the smoothness losses for ti and *t**i*+1.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] This leads to a more general understanding of a knot vector.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] where ti is repeated ji times for *i* = 1, …, *k* – 1.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A parametric curve on the interval [*a*,*b*] $G(t)={\bigl (}X(t),Y(t){\bigr )},\quad t\in [a,b]$ is a **spline curve** if both X and Y are spline functions of the same degree with the same extended knot vectors on that interval.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Suppose the polynomial pieces are to be of degree 2, and the pieces on [0, 1] and [1, 2] must join in value and first derivative (at *t* = 1) while the pieces on [1, 2] and [2, 3] join simply in value (at *t* = 2).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] (Note: while the polynomial piece 2*t* is not quadratic, the result is still called a quadratic spline.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] This demonstrates that the degree of a spline is the maximum degree of its polynomial parts.) The extended knot vector for this type of spline would be (0, 1, 2, 2, 3).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The next most simple spline has degree 1.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A closed linear spline (i.e, the first knot and the last are the same) in the plane is just a polygon.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A common spline is the **natural cubic spline**.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A cubic spline has degree 3 with continuity *C*2, i.e. the values and first and second derivatives are continuous.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Natural means that the second derivatives of the spline polynomials are zero at the endpoints of the interval of interpolation.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Thus, the graph of the spline is a straight line outside of the interval, but still smooth.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] In the field of 3D computer graphics, a **subdivision surface** (commonly shortened to **SubD surface** or **Subsurf**) is a curved surface represented by the specification of a coarser polygon mesh and produced by a recursive algorithmic method.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] The curved surface, the underlying *inner mesh*, can be calculated from the coarse mesh, known as the *control cage* or *outer mesh*, as the functional limit of an iterative process of subdividing each polygonal face into smaller faces that better approximate the final underlying curved surface.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] Less commonly, a simple algorithm is used to add geometry to a mesh by subdividing the faces into smaller ones without changing the overall shape or volume.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] The opposite operation is called *un-subdividing*, a type of mesh decimation that works on subdivided geometry.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] A subdivision surface algorithm is recursive in nature.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] The process starts with a base level polygonal mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] A **refinement scheme** is then applied to this mesh.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] This process takes that mesh and subdivides it, creating new vertices and new faces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] The positions of the new vertices in the mesh are computed based on the positions of nearby old vertices, edges, and/or faces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] In many refinement schemes, the positions of old vertices are also altered (possibly based on the positions of new vertices).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] This process produces a *denser* mesh than the original one, containing more polygonal faces (often by a factor of 4).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] This resulting mesh can be passed through the same refinement scheme again and again to produce more and more refined meshes.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] Each iteration is often called a subdivision *level*, starting at zero (before any refinement occurs).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] The *limit* subdivision surface is the surface produced from this process being iteratively applied infinitely many times.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] In practical use however, this algorithm is only applied a limited, and fairly small ( $\leq 5$ ), number of times.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] Mathematically, the neighborhood of an *extraordinary vertex* (non-4-valent node for quad refined meshes) of a subdivision surface is a spline with a parametrically singular point.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] Subdivision surface refinement schemes can be broadly classified into two categories: *interpolating* and *approximating*.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] In general, approximating schemes have greater smoothness, but the user has less overall control of the outcome.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] This is analogous to spline surfaces and curves, where Bézier curves are required to interpolate certain control points, while B-Splines are not (and are more approximate).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] Subdivision surface schemes can also be categorized by the type of polygon that they operate on: some function best for quadrilaterals (quads), while others primarily operate on triangles (tris).
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] After subdivision, the control points of the original mesh and the newly generated control points are interpolated on the limit surface.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] The earliest work was so-called "butterfly scheme" by Dyn, Levin and Gregory (1990), who extended the four-point interpolatory subdivision scheme for curves to a subdivision scheme for surfaces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] Zorin, Schröder and Sweldens (1996) noticed that the butterfly scheme cannot generate smooth surfaces for irregular triangle meshes and thus modified this scheme.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] Kobbelt (1996) further generalized the four-point interpolatory subdivision scheme for curves to the tensor product subdivision scheme for surfaces.
[src:subdivision-surfaces/subdivision-surface] In 1991, Nasri proposed a scheme for interpolating Doo-Sabin; while in 1993 Halstead, Kass, and DeRose proposed one for Catmull-Clark.
